In 2009, IHCL acquired Mumbai's iconic Sea Rock Hotel that suffered severe damage during the 1993 blasts. The location, on one end of the Bandra Band Stand perched on the rocky shore, was and is considered one of the best in the city. But challenges such as legal disputes, environmental clearances and increased floor space index, caused major hurdles for the new project to kickstart.

Finally, the construction of the newly christened Taj Bandstand will begin in 2025 and be completed in approximately four years with an investment of INR 2500 crore. The hotel will have 330 rooms, 85 luxury apartments, world-class dining, convention spaces and world-class facilities spread over 2 acres. 

Puneet Chhatwal, MD & CEO at IHCL, stated that Taj Bandstand will be the torchbearer of the iconic Taj brand for the next century, building on the legacy that began with The Taj Mahal Palace in 1903. The Bhoomi Pujan ceremony was held with the Hon’ble Chief Minister of Maharashtra, Devendra Fadnavis, and N. Chandrasekaran, Chairman, Tata Sons present.

With this addition, IHCL will have 17 hotels in Mumbai, including 5 under development Taj Bandstand is a tribute to Mumbai’s vibrant spirit and global prominence.

latestPosts.caption:
The 67th Annual Grammy Awards highlighted a significant moment for women artists, showcasing their achievements and contributions to the music industry. Beyoncé led the nominations with an impressive 11 nods, making history as the most-nominated artist ever with a total of 99 nominations. She won Album of the Year for Cowboy Carter, marking her first win in this prestigious category, and became the first Black woman to receive the Grammy for Best Country Album.

Sabrina Carpenter also had a standout night, winning Best Pop Solo Performance for her song 'Espresso' and being nominated across all major categories, including Best New Artist, where she competed against other talented female artists like Chappell Roan. 

The presence of multiple female nominees in key categories underscores a growing recognition of women's artistry in a historically male-dominated industry, reflecting a positive trend towards inclusivity and diversity within the Grammy Awards.

Kendrick Lamar's ""Not Like Us"" won both Record and Song of the Year, marking a historic achievement as the most decorated rap song in Grammy history.

From being an internet phenomenon to becoming a dietary mainstay, avocado is getting assimilated in the Indian way of life. What started out as a posh ingredient for fancy dishes avocado is now being part of dosa and parathas. Researches suggest that the avocado market in India is doubling year-on-year.

Outlook Luxe finds out how and why avocado became so wholeheartedly accepted in the country.

By: @sayonibhaduri

@karishma_sakhrani @westfaliafruitindia @chef_mitesh @indoisraelavocado @abokado.india

#OutlookLuxeDeepDive #avocadosinindia #avotoast #avosushi #avocado #guacamole #haasavocado

Dior's Spring/Summer 2025 haute couture show, held at the Musée Rodin in Paris, prominently featured the artwork of Indian artist Rithika Merchant. Her installation, "The Flowers We Grew," featured nine large-scale embroidered textile panels that transformed her delicate watercolour paintings into a striking tapestry, meticulously crafted by artisans from the Chanakya School of Craft.

The installation explores themes of womanhood and ancestral narratives, drawing inspiration from stories passed down through generations, particularly from Merchant's maternal lineage in Kerala, India.

Creative director Maria Grazia Chiuri, known for integrating women artists into her runway presentations, continues this tradition with Merchant, seamlessly merging fashion and art in a visually captivating display. The collection itself takes the sartorial creativity of previous centuries to disrupt the order of time and offer timelessness that is associated with the idea of transformation. It is rumoured that this showcase was Grazia Chiuri's last with the Dior.

Merchant's installation will remain open to the public until February 2, 2025, inviting visitors to experience this rich dialogue between narrative and craftsmanship.

After surviving and recovering from a devastating fire incident last year, Indian designer Gaurav Gupta and his life partner, Navkirat Sodhi find themselves in a phoenix-like recovery. The journey of healing took the form of a cosmic odyssey which was the core of his designs this year. Titled 'Across The Flame', Gupta's collection expresses the couple's version of an Astral Projection

The collection brings together hours of intricate artistry with new embroideries, such as raffia and micro pearls alongside the ghungroo (a tribal Indian metallic bell, used to intensify acoustics). Over 20,000 crystals from Preciosa have been used, renowned for their exceptional quality and brilliance, elevating the embellishments on key pieces throughout the collection. This season introduces new colours like ochre and twilight purple, space blue, symbolising transformation, alongside the brand’s signature shades of black, ivory and metallics. Gaurav Gupta’s jewellery pieces continue to evolve as symbols of resilience and rebirth.

latestPosts.caption:
NASA's Voyager 1 photograph of Earth, 'Pale Blue Dot', and its interpretation by astronomer and author Carl Sagan in his book of the same name inspired Indian couturier, Rahul Mishra's latest collection. 

Mishra showcased his version of 'The Pale Blue Dot' at the Paris Haute Couture Week runway. The colour theme of black and gold resembled the hues we best associate with the cosmos. The literal architectural elements of the ensembles express how the unsustainable urban landscapes are on a path of decay where nature will eventually and inevitably stake a claim on what is rightfully hers.

The detailing on the visually stunning pieces is meticulous and intricate and has been crafted by the 2000+ skilled craftsman at Mishra's Indian atelier.

"Our deliberate, measured processes not only provide sustainable employment but also allow us to slow down the consumption of natural resources. In doing so, we highlight the intrinsic value of ‘haute couture’—which celebrates craftsmanship, innovation, and purposeful design as a whole," Mishra said in his note.

@rahulmishra_7 @hautecoutureweek

latestPosts.caption:
The sixth edition of LVMH Watch Week saw nine LVMH watchmaking Maisons showcase their latest creations in an exclusive event on January 21-22, 2025 in New York. The Paris leg of the event will take place on January 30-31, 2025.

The prestigious Maisons that have regularly taken part in this event – Bvlgari, Hublot, TAG Heuer, Zenith, Daniel Roth and Gérald Genta – are joined in 2025 by three other iconic brands, Louis Vuitton, Tiffany & Co. and L’Epée 1839. 

Here are the five watched that stunned us at Outlook Luxe.

Gérald Genta Gentissima Oursin Fire Opal is the fourth piece in the Gentissima Oursin collection. The striking timepiece has individually screwed fire opal gems surrounding the circumference of the yellow gold case and orange cornelian dial of this limited-edition watch.

Crafted from 18k white gold, this luxurious and colourful take on the Zenith Chronomaster Sport is crowned by a bezel set in ‘Rainbow’ style with 50 baguette-cut gemstones. To enhance its style while preserving its functionality, a bright and colourful palette of 40 sapphires is punctuated with 10 baguette-cut diamonds indicating the 10 seconds. 

First introduced in 1948 as a mechanical timepiece, Serpenti was originally equipped with some of the finest movements of its era. With Serpenti Seduttori Automatic, Bvlgari is reconnecting with its heritage through the BVS100 Lady Solotempo, an all-new in-house automatic movement where the watch is powered by the kinetic energy of its wearer’s movements.

For the first time in the Hublot Spirit of Big Bang Chronograph collection, the cases and bezels are crafted in coloured ceramics that were previously only available in the round Big Bang shape: Sand Beige, Dark Green and Sky Blue, each limited to 200 pieces. 

The TAG Heuer Carrera Chronograph ignite the Glassbox design with a striking smoky black-to-purple gradient dial, following the success of the TAG Heuer Monaco Chronograph in purple. Inside the timepiece is the in-house Heuer 02 (TH20-00) movement, visible through the open caseback.

Nanagram Fine Jewels, a legacy brand with over 75 years of history, brings timeless luxury to Jaipur with its stunning flagship store.

From the world’s most perfectly faceted emerald sourced from the Ural mines to diamonds as unique as fingerprints, Nanagram offers more than just jewellery — they create heirlooms that tell stories of love and tradition.

In a symbolic gesture, Subhash Jain, the patriarch of Nanagram Fine Jewels, has dedicated an octahedral emerald to Maharaja Jai Singh II, the visionary founder of Jaipur.

by @dewanshrutika
